MapReduce Program to Calculate Frequency of a Given Word
Theory (Write in Exam)
Introduction

MapReduce is a programming model used for processing large amounts of data in a distributed environment. It is mainly used in Hadoop for parallel data processing.

The MapReduce framework works in two phases:

Mapper Phase
Reads the input data.
Converts the data into key-value pairs.
Emits intermediate output.
Reducer Phase
Receives grouped key-value pairs from the mapper.
Performs aggregation or counting operation.
Produces final output.
Word Frequency Problem

The objective is to calculate how many times a given word appears in a file.

Working of Program
The Mapper reads each line from the file.
It splits the line into words.

If the word matches the target word, it outputs:

word    1
The Reducer collects all values of the same word.
It adds all the counts and prints the final frequency.
Advantages of MapReduce
Processes large data efficiently.
Supports parallel execution.
Fault tolerant.
Scalable for big data applications.
Mapper Program (Python)
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

# Word to search
target_word = "hadoop"

for line in sys.stdin:
    words = line.strip().split()

    for word in words:
        if word.lower() == target_word.lower():
            print(f"{word}\t1")
Reducer Program (Python)
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import sys

current_word = None
current_count = 0

for line in sys.stdin:
    word, count = line.strip().split('\t')
    count = int(count)

    if current_word == word:
        current_count += count
    else:
        if current_word:
            print(f"{current_word}\t{current_count}")

        current_word = word
        current_count = count

# Print final result
if current_word:
    print(f"{current_word}\t{current_count}")
